metadata.name: f-emerald #446
metadata.description:
f-emerald generates unique ephemeral crystal-like structures that morph in space. each generation has a different shape, animation and colour palette. 

the crystals flicker with colours in the dark most of the time. there is, however, a 20% chance of obtaining a crystal on a bright background with a light colour palette and one out of ten structures is created in black and white.

metadata.name: Splinter #151
metadata.description:
This release marks my first anniversary on the fx(hash) platform! I want to extend a huge thank you to everyone for a fantastic year, and I'm looking forward to many more in the generative-art world!

The basic algorithm is an evolution of the one I used in my first release, Raked Strokes. Instead of mimicking a brush with parallel segments, I'm using perpendicular line segments to define the overall abstract shape and then drawing each line in a simulated media. This approach blends my first attempts at natural media with everything I've learned in the past year.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press 's' to save a screenshot. The image size is 2357x3000px
Press 'p' to pause/resume during drawing.

Features
- Base path shape: line, circle, diamond, or rectangle
- Elements defining the spacing and orientation of the line segments
- The base path painted in the background
- Monochrome, dark background, and selection of palettes
- Ink pen styling: thickness, quality, and background blocking
- Paint styling: color distribution, quality
- Shapes: triangle, polygons, criteria for insertion
- Shapes overdrawing: outlines or perpendicular segments

metadata.name: Azulejo #219
metadata.description:
Azulejo is a generative work made with p5.js

Behind this artwork, the author (eduxdux) had made a lot of research about tiling, the main references for this work were Athos Bulcão, Alexandre Mancini, and "Azulejo da igrejinha" by Cândido Portinari.

This artwork has 8 color palettes and 7 tile styles.
If you have lucky you can have a fully filled tile.

This work is participating in the FxHash anniversary event (#fxhashturnsone) and 10% of the royalties go to the Save Pakistan

Eduxdux November 2022

metadata.name: Tessera #94
metadata.description:
Tessera is a project inspired by historical Mosaics. A tessera (Latin) is a small individual tile, usually formed in the shape of a square, used for making a mosaic. As the world's first "pixel art", Tessera is a tribute to this craft. This collection is made solely of rectangles on a two-dimensional canvas into an abstract mosaic flow with a three-dimensional effect.

Press s in live mode to download.

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje Oktober 2022

metadata.name: Hayata! #51
metadata.description:
Hayata! emerged from my brief research on one-dimensional cellular automata (CA) and developed into a full project, since the resulting patterns were much more interesting than I had expected, especially when you mix the rules together.
Since the rules of this CA are so simple, they have something ancient, original and mysterious about them, like the I-Ching or other oracle methods. So I tried to give the CA a worthy frame by making the texture look aged and handmade.
I hope that your oracle only predicts good things for you :)
------
F.D. Berlin, October '22

Size: Between 1600px and 3200px both height and width.
Libraries used: chroma.js

metadata.name: k3rnel #155
metadata.description:
Self-organizing future-jazz geometry for like-minded pixel based neighbourhoods. 


********
Glossary
********

'Self-organization' → the process by which individuals organize their communal behaviour to create global order by interactions amongst themselves rather than through external intervention or instruction.

'Future-jazz-geometry' → propulsive syncopated visual rhythms, polyphonic ensemble playing, varying degrees of improvisation, and often deliberate distortions of pitch and timbre.

'Like-minded' → sharing the same opinions, ideas, or interests. 

'Pixel' → the smallest addressable element in an all points addressable display device; so it is the smallest controllable element of a picture represented on the screen.

'Neighbourhood' → a spatial unit, in which face-to-face social interactions occur.

Touch to listen, go fullscreen

metadata.name: Störungen #206
metadata.description:
Störungen is an exercise in suprematism in generative art. Not a new concept by any means, but (hopefully) uniquely applied.

In this work a single line is drawn from the center of the artwork, spiraling out and being perturbed by various constraints and disturbed by various controlling forces. These perturbations produce different illusions and, when combined, create feeling.

This piece is created in p5js, but is also intended to be plotted. Plotting will not allow for the blurring or color in the piece, but will instead give you a single color version of the perturbed spiral that you can print.

Open the token in a new window and:
- add &highres=true to the URL to get a highres image for printing
- add &svg=true to have the program create a plottable SVG
- double-click to download a PNG or SVG

metadata.name: Obliques #215
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)

metadata.name: Puzzled Picture #24
metadata.description:
This work is composed of a combination of grids with line patterns, like my previous work "Infinite Animation" (Project #15745).  However, whereas the previous work was characterized by simplicity and regularity, this one is much more chaotic.

First, while in the previous work the grids were fixed at 3 x 3, in this work there are variations from 5 x 5 to 20 x 20. 
And in this work, it is YOU who rotates the grid. Clicking on a grid rotates it 90 degrees and changes the image. If you have difficulty locating the grid, press the "g" key on the keyboard to display a guide (for touch devices, long press to show/hide the guide).
If you get tired of clicking, you can ask your computer to help you. You can toggle the animation mode with the "a" key on the keyboard (for touch devices, swipe up to turn on the mode, swipe down to turn it off). In animation mode, the computer rotates a random grid at regular intervals. (The surrounding frame turns green in animation mode.)

The fun of generative art lies in finding value, or to stretch the point a bit, destiny, in the random coincidences created by computers. Therefore, it is not aesthetically pleasing to artificially modify the derived result later. However, dynamism is also a characteristic of digital art. The fluidity of the results is probably one of its interesting features. I experimented with it in my previous work, "Abstract Calligraphy"(Project #15384), and have done it more characteristically in this project.

This picture is like a puzzle game, but there is no correct answer. No, there may be a correct answer. It depends on your aesthetic sense. Let's enjoy collaborating with the computer!
